<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / FT Review of Business Books (10): Get my product to the
market on time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRODUCT DEVELOPMENT: AN INTEGRATED APPROACH
By David Inwood and Jean Hammond
Kogan Page Pounds 16.95 194 pages
The company which gets to market first can often set a standard and
establish a lead which its competitors can never destroy. So the speed with
which new products or services can be developed and put on sale can make a
significant contribution to company profits.
The Japanese have established a strong reputation for bringing products
rapidly to market. Japanese companies in the motor industry have brought
development lead times down to just 43 months compared with the 63 months
taken by their US competitors, though the Americans have started to respond.
Just how a company should set about improving its management of product
development is explained in this practical guide. The authors, respectively
a consultant and an organisational psychologist, identify their target
market as the corporate strategist, the project manager and the leaders and
members of product development teams.
The techniques described are most likely to form part of a large company's
management armoury but the principles could be applied, with benefit, by the
medium-sized business.
The pace of new product launches in a range of highly visible sectors such
as video recorders, cameras and motor vehicles has encouraged high
expectations among consumers. But the failure rate for new high-technology
products is high.
Traditional methods of developing new products are no longer appropriate,
the authors argue. In the past the process would start with a technical
product development team turning an idea into a design. The production
engineering department would convert the design into a product; and a
production team would devise the means of manufacture, including tooling and
training. Finally marketing would launch and sell the product.
This way of working is often known as the 'over-the-wall' approach to
product development. One department does its job in isolation and then
passes the project with little or no discussion on to the next. Objectives
may be lost as the project is handed on; no one is in overall control; there
is often a need for lots of changes late in the day; and the process is
expensive and slow.
The new approach, which has been pioneered by the Japanese, is for an
integrated management team to develop these various strands in parallel.
Outline market research will be carried out at the same time as an
investigation of the technical possibilities. At the same time the
production department will begin its planning.
However, there are limits to this approach and complete parallel working is
not really possible. Until the concept has been worked out and the
specifications drawn up it would be suicidal to run technical, production
and marketing development at the same time.
The label which has been applied to this method of working is 'simultaneous
or concurrent engineering', though this has the unfortunate implication that
product development is still at heart an engineering process. The authors
prefer the term 'integrated product development.' This requires the
creation, at an early stage, of a multi-disciplinary team which can ensure
there is a consistent approach. As far as possible, the different processes
should take place in parallel, though in practice some areas will have to
overlap rather than run in complete parallel.
Ideally projects should be kept small and companies should aim for
incremental improvements rather than big advances. The more ambitious the
development, the more likely it is to become bogged down by problems. This
can create a vicious circle of infrequent product launches and a consequent
loss of feedback from customers, leading to expensive failure. Controls are
then tightened, senior management becomes involved and development slows
even further.
But while incremental change can reduce the risks involved in product
development, it can be pushed too far, the authors warn. Too many changes
cause problems for product support and can leave customers who have bought
an earlier model feeling short-changed.
Even when there is careful planning, product development is never a certain
thing, with fixed and knowable goals at the start. Product development teams
must therefore be prepared to modify their plans as a project advances. If
insuperable problems emerge they may have to axe a project altogether.
But by adopting a phased approach they can achieve a better management of
risk. Often the idea of risk appears to defy rational thought, but there are
methods of controlling risk which do not necessarily require the use of
refined numeric techniques.
Risks may be categorised as internal, resulting, for example, from a lack of
resources or the use of an unfamiliar technology. Or they may be external,
taking the form of a pre-emptive product launch by a competitor or a change
in public taste. They may relate to the technology involved or to the
marketing approach adopted.
By discussing risk in advance, a product team can assess both the
probability of a particular threat and its potential severity. Managers can
then take steps to avoid the risk, to share it with, say, a supplier, or to
insure against it. They can modify a product or commission outside research
and development to solve a particular problem.
This handbook provides a thorough, if somewhat dry, account of how to speed
up product development. It would have been improved by the use of case
histories and by a more comprehensive glossary to guide the beginner through
the jargon. But it deals with a subject which companies ignore at their
peril.
</TEXT>
