<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (7): Last orders for the
water of life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON COATES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTCH MISSED: THE LOST DISTILLERIES OF SCOTLAND
by Brian Townsend
Neil Wilson Publishing Pounds 14.99 160 pages
Whether it is coal mining, motor cycles or televisions, sentimentality about
'lost' industries is rather a British speciality. But when it comes to the
uneconomic distilleries of Scotland, the pining becomes almost inconsolable.
What a tragic loss, goes the cry, as a bottle of 64-year old Dallas Dhu is
sold at auction for Pounds 4,400.
Such hand-wringing is misplaced. It fails to take account of the unique
conditions that led to a distillery's foundation and shaped its initial
market. It also ignores the widespread failure of a hopelessly atomised
industry to adapt to, and influence, changed consumer tastes.
Brian Townsend is a devotee of the lost dram. His book is part history and
part guide to the ruins. The 'water of life' probably came to Scotland from
Ireland in the late 15th century, explaining in part peat-rich Islay's early
pre-eminence. Family bothy distilleries remained ubiquitous north of the
Highland line even after the Industrial Revolution, exploiting the special
qualities of their location - whether peat, water, barley or all three.
The North also stood out for its successful evasion of duty. This owed much
to family ingenuity, but also to the localised nature of the market. Many a
magistrate was struck with compassion when his importunate estate supplier
stood before him.
But ironically such parochialism does much to explain the demise of the
smaller distilleries. Take, for example, their reaction to the 1820s reform
of the excise system. It now became viable to distil on a larger scale, and
such household names as Johnny Walker date to that time. But the smaller
distilleries rarely combined. Not for the first time in British
manufacturing, long-term thinking was at a premium in a long-term industry.
Distilling in the 19th century offered better returns on investment than
selling grain to mills, but quality varied between distillations and
according to harvests. Continuity and reliability of supply were secured
only by outside intervention. By blending malt with the less flavoursome,
but more consistent, grain whisky increasingly produced in the larger
distilleries, the new whisky merchants could ensure supplies to the
lucrative distant markets, particularly London. Further growth came through
exploiting the nascent glass bottling process which helped to reduce prices.
The fact that expansion was largely the result of action by non-distillers
is significant. The distillers were often woefully under-capitalised and
their focus on local markets meant a large slice of the profits went to the
merchants when, in the later 19th century, consumption increased among such
groups as the brandy-deprived monied classes and Empire exiles.
Townsend chronicles the almost yearly changes of ownership among the
proliferating, but ultimately-doomed distilleries, as new owners sought
unsuccessfully to cash in at the local level. When the boost in whisky
consumption was ended by a combination of temperance, a big rise in duties
courtesy of Lloyd George and war, the core weaknesses of the smaller
distillers, particularly in the west of Scotland, were ruthlessly exposed.
Depression and the organising mind of Distillers Company's chairman, William
Ross, rationalised the industry and cut back the over-supply in the
inter-war years. Once both domestic and export market conditions improved
after 1950, a smaller, but more outward-looking industry developed, notably
in Speyside. The fact that some of the most successful new operations are
family-owned shows that past lessons have been learnt. Japanese inward
investment has included distillery ownership, with tourist potential well
exploited.
Old habits die hard, however, and Townsend's affinity with his subject
prompts him to echo the industry's plea for 'fairer' tax and tariff
treatment. But British governments have a well-proven ability to raise
revenue successfully from duties, while other countries seem set to ensure
their own distilleries prosper, regardless of the Uruguay Round.
</TEXT>
<XX>
