<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (6): Brent smoothes oil's
troubled waters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EVOLUTION OF OIL MARKETS: TRADING INSTRUMENTS AND THEIR ROLE IN PRICE
FORMATION
by Joe Roeber
Royal Institute of International Affairs, 90 pages, Pounds 12.50
OIL MARKETS AND PRICES
by Paul Horsnell and Robert Mabro
Oxford University Press, 334 pages, Pounds 39.50
Asked how the oil markets work, most would probably say they were run by the
big oil companies and OPEC. That may have been so 10 years ago, but today
things are very different.
OPEC's grip on oil prices began to slip after the oil shocks of the 1980s
and finally gave way in 1985-86 when Saudi Arabia stopped playing the role
of 'swing producer'. Since then, open markets have taken over, and oil is
now traded like any other commodity with published prices and all the
derivative trappings.
The markets revolve round a few 'marker' crudes, such as Brent from the
North Sea, West Texas Intermediate in the US and Dubai in the Gulf. The
market players are a tight-knit - and shrinking - group of large oil
companies, Wall Street investment houses and Japanese traders. According to
Horsnell and Mabro, 174 traders were identified in the late 1980s, but now
the core of those who really matter numbers a mere 15.
In the 'wet markets' for actual delivery, oil is traded on the basis of
cargoes using a complicated system which anticipates three-day loading slots
at some future date in the future.
In the dated Brent market, a cargo is traded round the market in a kind of
pass-the-parcel, and whoever holds it at the end of the afternoon is 'five
o'clocked' and has to buy it. There are wrinkles, like the 'tolerance game'
which enables traders to trade on the fact that cargoes may have variations,
or tolerances, up to 5 per cent.
The evolution of derivative markets such as futures and options, (the 'paper
markets') has opened the way for sophisticated trading techniques in which
tax minimisation, hedging or pure speculation provide the motivation as much
as a simple desire to buy crude oil.
The key question, though, is what drives the oil price if it is no longer
OPEC? Both books reach the same conclusion: Brent is the key because many
OPEC members price off it, and other markets are linked through arbitrage.
Politics plays a role, but as Horsnell and Mabro point out, it is
anticipation of what OPEC may do rather than what it actually does which
influences prices.
The markets are far from perfect: they can be manipulated, they lack the
ability to trade certain types of crude oil, and the best price information
depends on newspaper reporters speaking to the right people at the right
time. But both books contain pleas to government to resist the temptation to
try and make them better.
Readers can choose between these two publications. Roeber has compressed the
subject to a handy size, but the result is often dense and heavy going.
Anyone with a serious interest in the oil market would do better to invest
the time and money in Horsnell and Mabro whose account is both fascinating
and scholarly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
