<PROFILE>_AN-DLACFAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (4): Gold fever, and how to
catch it
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORLD OF GOLD: THE INSIDE STORY OF WHO MINES, WHO MARKETS AND WHO BUYS
GOLD
by Timothy Green
Rosendale Press, Pounds 21 388 pages
It is 25 years since Tim Green became entranced by the mystique of gold and
quit his job as editor of Illustrated London News to write the first version
of this book. Time has not diminished his enthusiasm nor his ability to
bring the world of gold to life with writing that has crystal clarity and
huge dollops of humour. These flow from the anecdotes he has picked up
travelling well over 1m miles in a global search for the gossip which is
essential to an understanding of a deeply secretive business.
He contends that during those 25 years the world of gold has changed more
than in the preceding three or four thousand. He has seen the price of gold
move from Dollars 35 a troy ounce in 1970, up to Dollars 850 in 1980 and
back down to Dollars 350 in 1990. But he cannot decided whether the decision
by international governments to end the fixed price of gold in 1968 or the
subsequent radical transformation in communications was the more important
influence.
According to Green: 'It meant that, for many new players in the market,
volatility, not stability, was the chief attraction: to them it did not
matter whether the price went up or down, as long as it moved. The
communications network brought everyone together, round the world, round the
clock, and made the gold price a moveable feast.'
The gold market has been dishing up futures, options, warrants in ever more
exotic combinations to woo a new clientele whose prime concern was often a
piece of the action without the acute embarrassment of having to take
delivery of a single ounce.
Green argues that this has left the gold market's future very much in the
hands of the New York investment funds. Futures, options, swaps and related
instruments today make up an estimated Dollars 10,000bn in investments
traded both over the counter and on regulated exchanges.
'The gold market is only a side-show in this revolution much of the time,'
Green points out. 'But mobile money can be switched into it in an afternoon
if the mood is there, as happened in 1993 when high-profile players like Sir
James Goldsmith and George Soros kick-started a rally that ran from Dollars
340 to Dollars 400, triggering not only a scramble for cover, but luring the
weight of serious money from managed futures funds who saw gold as the
play-of-the-day.'
Such a wave can easily swamp momentarily the 'rather modest' physical market
in gold. Green puts the total value of newly-mined gold each year at less
than Dollars 30bn (at Dollars 400 an ounce). 'This is petty cash when one
considers that Dollars 1,130bn is traded every day in currency markets.'
Managed futures funds have more than Dollars 20bn at their disposal and
think nothing of zipping in an out for 100,000 ounces of gold or more at a
clip. 'Annual trading volume on futures thus dwarfs conventional physical
markets.'
Green also shows the way tactics in gold options and futures have become
increasingly dictated by technical charting and computer trading which are
all about 'buy' and 'sell' signals and give short shrift to the fundamentals
of who mines and who buys gold. 'Detecting when those signals may be
triggered is a part of a dealer's life. Every bullion bank has its in-house
chartist, plotting support points, moving averages and momentum indicators
or oscillators as they are known in the US.'
Green tells of a colleague who ventured to tackle a fund manager after a New
York seminar on the growth of managed money, with the suggestion that the
mine production numbers might mean something. 'He had his head snapped off.
'I don't care if South Africa produces one ounce or one million,' the
manager said, turning on his heel and leaving. His fund looks after a modest
Dollars 650m, some of which may shift into gold from time to time, when the
computer says so.'
This book is not for that fund manager. Green gives us gold's fascinating
history as well as showing us many of today's great gold mines through an
expert's eyes. He explains how new technology - and a climbing price -
spurred the gold rushes in Australia and North America during the 1980s.
The broad message of this book will please the bulls. Green suggests that
gold has come to terms with its new environment while the broad canvas of
supply and demand looks promising. Gold 'has come through what could have
been a traumatic transition from being principally a monetary metal to one
principally used in jewellery, but with the added zest of continuing
universal acceptance as a means of exchange and as a speculative or
investment vehicle.'
</TEXT>
