<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (2): Korea: a tale of two
systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE KOREAN ECONOMIES: A COMPARISON OF NORTH AND SOUTH
by Eui-Gak Hwang
Clarendon Press, Pounds 40 380 pages
It is novel for a book about development economics to open with a dedication
to 'the Lord Jesus Christ . . . foremost supporter, moral economist and
political adviser in my life', but that is how Eui-Gak Hwang introduces his
study of North and South Korea.
Hwang, professor of economics at the Korea University in Seoul, goes on to
top each chapter with either a Biblical text or a piece of oriental poetry.
The reader thus starts to speculate exactly which Biblical extract will come
up next, for example to set the tone for a chapter on Public Finance in
North and South Korea; the answer, appropriately enough, is Isaiah's
prophetic roaring that claims must be supported by evidence. In the
conclusion, Biblical reference also comes in handy to duck a judgment on the
likely pace of Korea's surely inevitable reunification process. Here, the
author cites Proverbs: 'In his heart a man plans his course, but the Lord
determines his steps.'
Most of this unusual book is devoted to a painstaking assembly of parallel
data about the two Koreas. Hwang goes to great lengths to try to render
comparisons between the two meaningful, which is no easy task given the
secretive nature of the North Korean authorities and the problem of
interpreting that data which does exist, especially with regard to exchange
rates.
His underlying purpose, however, appears to be to do his bit for the
reunification debate, by adding to our understanding of the historical
relationship between the economies of north and south and their potential
complementarity in the future. Hwang has worked in Germany and thought about
the problems of bringing together the unruly offspring of communism and
post-colonial capitalism.
The historical picture presented does not conform to the western caricature
whereby after a period of domination by Japan, the second world war bestowed
upon South Korea American patronage, market capitalism and prosperity, while
the north chose autarkic Marxist-Leninism, leading to economic collapse and
poverty.
Prior to the division of the country in 1945, Korea south of the 38th
parallel was the poorer, more agricultural part of the peninsula. The north
had the minerals and most of the heavy industry.
During the 1960s and early 1970s, Hwang supports the view that the communist
northern economy grew more rapidly than the south's, where a combination of
political confusion and natural disadvantage impeded progress. Although it
is clear that the south recovered from these setbacks and became in the
1980s one of the outstanding economic performers in the world, it was not
until at least the mid-1970s and possibly not until the 1980s that the south
actually overtook the north in terms of per capita GNP.
During the 1980s, in spite of a Deng Xiao-Ping inspired 'opening up',
economic data from the north became ever scarcer, contributing to the
impression that successive plans were failing to hit their loudly proclaimed
targets. But even in the 1980s, when Hwang argues the central planning
system failed to deal with the growing complexities of the northern economy,
his figures suggest annual growth in the north never fell below 1.7 per cent
in local currency terms, exceeding 12 per cent in 1982 and 1983. In the
1980s, however, the south streaked ahead; by 1989 the south's dollar gnp per
capita was double that of the north. By some measures, it is now four or
five times that of its neighbour.
Even this, Hwang implies, should not be taken crudely as a triumph of one
system over the other. Although he acknowledges the inestimable value of
greater personal freedom in the south and the more widespread availability
of consumer choice, he notes disapprovingly the wider gap between rich and
poor in South Korea and adds that 'other indicators, such as life
expectancy, mortality, literacy, and other physical quality-of-life indexes,
merely serve to indicate that there exists no significant difference between
the north and the south.' Not for this author much regard for the regular
current rumours of food riots and impending political collapse.
Hwang thus implies that North Korea's future might be better foreseen in
comparison with that of China or even with other politically authoritarian,
free traders in the region, than with post-glasnost Russia or Albania. The
north may have a totalitarian system, dominated for half a century by the
unpredictable Kim Il Sung, but it has dabbled with capitalism, through joint
ventures, especially with Japan. North Korea, the author says, has an
economy which is 'on a road to quasi-market principles at least.'
Some will think this altogether too optimistic and even Hwang says that the
cultural re-harmonisation of the two Koreas will present serious
difficulties, especially given the rapid widening of the economic gap in
recent years. Given North Korea's recent high-risk manoeuvres on its nuclear
weapons programme, the politics as well as the economics appear to point to
measured rather than sudden progress in the drama of re-unification.
</TEXT>
<XX>
