<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / International Company News: US broker takes super computing
to Wall St
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The most powerful computer introduced to the financial markets was switched
on yesterday by Merrill Lynch, the US's biggest broking firm.
In a sign of the growing importance of computing power to Wall Street,
Merrill has paid more than Dollars 1.75m for what is believed to be the
first supercomputer to support trading in the financial markets.
Supercomputers are high-performance machines capable of processing large
amounts of data very rapidly.
Mr John Galonte, a Merrill Lynch first vice-president, said the machine's
ability to process information was intended to give the firm an edge in its
trading activities. 'We want to improve the timeliness of some of our
calculations,' he said.
The machine, a Cray Research MP2E with two processors, is described by the
maker as 'the middle to low end of our product range'. Supercomputers are
used mainly for forecasting the weather or in other government or academic
applications, though companies in the aerospace, motor manufacturing,
chemicals and energy industries have begun to use them in recent years.
The need for greater computing power follows the development of both
derivatives and arbitrage trading, which rely on the analysis of large
amounts of financial data.
</TEXT>
