<DATE>931130
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / International Company News: Skandia to oppose merger by
Volvo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Volvo's campaign to win support for the merger of its car and truck
operations with Renault received a setback last night when Skandia, an
insurance company holding about 4 per cent of its voting capital, decided to
oppose it.
The move is a blow to Volvo's hopes of winning approval at a shareholders'
meeting on December 7.
Skandia said the merger was neither in the interests of Volvo shareholders
nor the country. It brought to around 8.5 per cent the number of votes
opposing the deal.
Aktiespararna, the small shareholders' association whose members represent
up to 6 per cent, is also opposed.
Volvo is certain of about 30 per cent of the votes but of six Swedish
institutional shareholders to have declared their stance, only two support
it.
Skandia's decision will narrow the chances of Volvo winning the majority it
needs to fend off a legal challenge from Aktiespararna. Even if the deal
goes through, Skandia said it will join a growing move among major
shareholders to reshape the Volvo board, a step principally aimed against Mr
Pehr Gyllenhammar, the chairman.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Volvo.
    Renault.
    Skandia Group Insurance.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
