<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Bristol Evening Post at Pounds 3.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An 80 per cent higher contribution from its newspaper and printing
activities helped the Bristol Evening Post lift pre-tax profits by 17 per
cent to Pounds 3.1m in the 26 weeks to September 30.
The regional newspapers and retailing group had been stalked until May by Mr
David Sullivan, publisher of the Sunday Sport and Daily Sport, who was keen
to move into mainstream newspapers.
Mr Stanley Clarke, chairman, said the possible imposition of VAT on
newspaper cover prices made it difficult to comment on the prospects for the
second half of the year.
Group turnover declined by almost 3 per cent to Pounds 30.1m, with the
contribution from newspapers and printing down at Pounds 16.8m (Pounds 17m)
and from retail activities down 5 per cent at Pounds 12.2m (Pounds 12.9m).
The latter was mainly due to 'an acceleration of the disposal of kiosk
shops'.
Profits from newspapers and printing grew to Pounds 1.31m (Pounds 731,000),
though Mr Clarke said that the circulations of the two main newspapers - the
Bristol Evening Post and the Western Daily Press - remained depressed. The
kiosks reorganisation led to the retailing side making less at Pounds
215,000 (Pounds 288,000). Features agencies and film production was flat at
Pounds 47,000, while transport and vehicle repair lifted profits to Pounds
249,000 (Pounds 202,000).
The group offset the increased reorganisation costs of Pounds 342,000
(Pounds 244,000) by profits from the sale of further Reuters shares which
accrued Pounds 371,000 (Pounds 276,000).
Earnings advanced to 8.47p (7.27p) per share and the interim dividend is
lifted to 4.25p (4p).
</TEXT>
