<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Nadir trial judge 'hurt' by probe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Justice Tucker, the judge in the case of fugitive tycoon Mr Asil Nadir,
yesterday told how he was 'shocked and angry' when he learnt of an
investigation into an alleged plot to bribe him.
In comments after he had received an apology from the Serious Fraud Office
for the offence caused to him last November, when questions were raised as
to whether he should remain in charge of the Nadir trial, he said: 'I was
very offended and hurt when I heard these allegations made in open court. I
have known from the start it was arrant and outrageous nonsense.'
The apology came during an application made in court by Mr Andrew Nicol on
behalf of The Independent newspaper to lift a reporting ban on court
proceedings on November 6 last year, in which details of the allegations and
the high-level police inquiry into them first emerged.
Mr David Calvert-Smith, representing the SFO, said it now realised the
allegations were 'spurious and groundless'.
After receiving a report of the police investigation the Crown Prosecution
Service said this month that allegations of a Pounds 3.5m bribery attempt
had not been sustained. The allegations were said to have been made by a
known informant and a female business acquaintance of Mr Nadir who are now
believed to be in northern Cyprus.
Mr Nadir, who is accused of fraud involving Pounds 30m and was head of Polly
Peck, has made his home in northern Cyprus since fleeing Britain.
Mr Calvert-Smith told the judge yesterday: 'We apologise deeply for the
offence your Lordship felt, but we were attempting to act in the very best
interests of the trial.'
Mr Justice Tucker agreed to lift the contempt order, saying the only reason
he made it in the first place was to try to ensure Mr Nadir would receive a
fair trial, not to protect his own position.
At the November 6 hearing the judge was told by Mr Robert Owen QC, then
prosecuting for the SFO, that there was 'a probability' that officers
involved in investigating what he only described as 'matters' would wish to
interview him.
</TEXT>
