<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Surge in factory output expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturing output is set to rise sharply in the next few months, boosting
recovery hopes, says a survey from the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and
Supply published today.
The survey indicates an increase in orders and a fall in stock levels while
delivery times have lengthened. All these indicators point to a continuation
of the recent relatively strong growth in manufacturing.
An index published by the institute giving a view of output trends came out
at 54.2 this month, the highest figure since April. In October it was 53.6.
The November figure indicates that the rate of expansion in manufacturing
activity has increased for the second successive month. It also shows that
activity has increased compared with the previous month for the 10th
successive month.
The index is calculated from data supplied every month by purchasing
managers in 300 manufacturing companies. A figure above 50 shows that
activity is higher than in the previous month. A number higher than the one
recorded in the month before shows expansion has accelerated.
The output component of the index was at 59.3 this month, indicating a rise
in the level of production for the 13th successive month. Full order books
and a high volume of sales were widely reported as the main reasons for the
continued upturn.
The new orders component of the index came in at 55.8 this month, down from
56.3 in October but well above the levels of about 50 in both August and
September.
The survey shows raw material prices were stable in November in line with
the general view that inflationary pressures are muted. Companies reported
an overall expansion in staff numbers during the month, fitting in with
matching recent evidence that unemployment is falling.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
