<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Abu Dhabi firm on BCCI payout
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government of Abu Dhabi, majority shareholder in the collapsed Bank of
Credit and Commerce International, appears to have ruled out any increase in
payments it would make to compensate creditors.
It yesterday rejected any suggestion that it was preparing to raise its
payments as part of a negotiated settlement with the liquidators to the
bank.
Speculation has surrounded the shape of new proposals since the unexpected
decision of the Luxembourg Appeal Court at the end of last month to reject
an agreement between Abu Dhabi and the liquidators.
Abu Dhabi is believed to have ruled out any increase in its contribution
from between Dollars 1.7bn (Pounds 1.1bn) and Dollars 2.2bn, which it would
have paid in exchange for a waiver of legal claims against it.
It said it was 'considering options to overcome the technical problems
thrown up' by the court.
