<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Expenditure watchdog attacks market testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The introduction of market testing into the civil service is making it
harder to keep track of public expenditure, says Sir John Bourn, head of the
National Audit Office.
The office, which is parliament's public expenditure watchdog, has no right
of access to the books of companies that win contracts for providing public
services, Sir John told the Commons public accounts committee yesterday.
Sir John contrasted his lack of power to inspect contractors' papers with
those of the Audit Commission, which has the right of access in auditing
local authority and health service activities.
Apart from the defence and transport ministries, most departments and
agencies had no experience in letting contracts, Sir John told the MPs. The
NAO was keen to monitor the great expansion in the programme, which he
regarded as 'an area of concern'.
Sir John said that the NAO should be given more auditing work for more than
1,400 central government quangos. Most of these non-departmental public
bodies are audited by private-sector accountancy firms, chosen by the
secretary of state in charge of their sponsoring department in consultation
with the Treasury.
Mr Robert Sheldon, chairman of the committee, expressed concern about the
way that accountancy firms used audits to win more lucrative consultancy
work.
Mr Terry Davis, Labour MP for Birmingham Hodge Hill, said opportunities to
find ways of improving value for money in public services could be lost by
excluding the NAO, which could generalise from the experience of several
cases.
Sir John also said the office was paying increasing attention to examining
the vulnerability of management systems to fraud. There was a rising
incidence of white-collar crime associated with computers, he said.
</TEXT>
