<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / City foresees life ban on Levitt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Speculation is mounting in the City that Mr Roger Levitt, chairman of the
collapsed Levitt Group, will be the first individual banned for life from
the investment business.
The Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, has the
power under Section 59 of the Financial Services Act to ban individuals who
it considers have damaged investors' interests severely, but it has never
used those powers.
The chairman of one self-regulating organisation said yesterday: 'Mr Levitt
is a classic example of where Section 59 ought to apply.'
SIB declined yesterday to say whether it intended to apply Section 59 in the
Levitt case.
The use of Section 59 in the Levitt case would meet concern in the financial
services sector that the light sentence given to Mr Levitt has undermined
the regulators' position and that a sterner deterrent to such conduct is
needed.
Leading City figures have expressed frustration at the sentencing of Mr
Levitt to 180 hours of community service for misleading regulators about his
company's health.
The company later collapsed with debts of Pounds 34m, causing millions of
pounds of losses to individual investors.
The Investors Compensation Scheme, funded by a levy on the industry, paid
out Pounds 616,000 to 25 investors, most of whom lost far more than the
Pounds 47,000 ceiling on claims.
Mr Joel Joffe, former deputy chairman of life insurer Allied Dunbar, said
the sentence given to Mr Levitt would 'do great harm to the regulatory
system'.
Mr Garry Heath, the chief executive of the National Federation of
Independent Financial Advisers, said the regulator had acted properly. He
said: 'The judge has let us down.'
Fimbra, the self-regulating organisation for financial advisers, yesterday
said it could only re-emphasise that it was disappointed that the tough
action by the regulators had not been mirrored by the sentence. 'On the
positive side, Mr Levitt's company was stopped from trading three years ago
by Fimbra, which shows the need for effective regulation to be there to stop
those unfit to do business. In this and many other cases, we can stop them
for good.'
Letters, Page 18
</TEXT>
