<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Three faults caused big Tube breakdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A combination of three separate failures was responsible for the
unprecedented breakdown which crippled a large part of the London
underground network during the past six days, it was revealed yesterday.
Much of the blame for the widespread failure was traced to two burnt-out
cables in one of the two power stations supplying the network. But a fault
in a cable running from the second power station and a defective transformer
elsewhere combined to bring the system down, London Underground said.
These faults led to the most serious breakdown on the Underground network
since the second world war and prompted calls for increased spending on its
ageing infrastructure. At one stage 20,000 people were trapped in trains in
tunnels.
London Underground said it expected to operate a full service from today.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said investment in the Underground
was at its highest level for three decades in spite of complaints in the
Commons from Labour MPs.
Mr MacGregor also said that modernisation of the Central Line, which was at
the heart of last week's chaos, amounted to Pounds 750m and was due to
finish in 1995.
Mr Denis Tunnicliffe, London Underground managing director, said Mr
MacGregor was right, but that there were 30 years of underspending to make
up. In addition, annual spending of up to Pounds 800m promised in 1991 had
since been reduced by more than Pounds 200m a year.
'If we had received the money we were promised, the power supply system
would have been more up-to-date,' he said. 'It is unattractive spending,
with no charisma, but it is vital.'
London Underground put the cost of the breakdown at Pounds 2m, because of
lost revenue, ticket-holder compensation and the cost of 24-hour engineering
work needed to track down the fault.
The problems of the past six days might have been avoided if London
Underground had been able to take power directly from the national grid, but
only parts of the network are connected, Mr Tunnicliffe said. It is working
on a project which will allow the entire Underground to draw on the grid.
Engineers had originally been looking for the fault at the eastern end of
the network. But discovered from data print-outs that the main problem,
burnt-out cable, was at its Lots Road power station in Chelsea, west London.
The Central Line had been worst affected because the equipment for shutting
down the line in the event of a leakage of current was very old. It is to be
replaced next year.
</TEXT>
