<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Debts of Pounds 34m before collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Whatever the legality of Mr Roger Levitt's financial manoeuvres, the Levitt
Group was in dire trouble, with debts of Pounds 34m, before its final
collapse in December 1990.
Salaries and other costs were wildly out of control. Sales figures were
boosted in unorthodox ways, giving a falsely optimistic impression of the
company's actual business. In addition, the company's internal book-keeping
was, by common consent, a complete mess.
According to the Serious Fraud Office, the company made a loss of Pounds 13m
between January 1989 and June 1990 and was heading for the rocks.
The total prosecution case against Mr Levitt, intended to be brought in two
trials, alleged widespread fraud by him and others in an attempt to keep the
company going.
The substance of the raft of criminal charges involved:
Improper inducements to attract investors' funds.
The routing of investors' money into the Levitt Group's company account to
keep it afloat.
The misrepresentation by Mr Levitt of Pounds 21m obtained through loans and
other sources as the result of genuine business.
The falsification of documents to turn the Pounds 13m loss into a Pounds 13m
profit, presenting the outside world with a false picture of the company's
viability.
The deception of Fimbra to maintain membership of the regulatory body.
The last charge was the only one to which Mr Levitt pleaded guilty. The
others have been left on the file, not to be acted upon. Mr Levitt maintains
his innocence with regard to these.
The Levitt Group went into liquidation owing money to assorted creditors.
The largest of these, technically, was Mr Levitt himself, owed some Pounds
22m as a result of investments in his company made in his own name. These
transactions, however, were the subject of some of the charges that will not
now be pursued.
The next largest creditors were Barclays and Midland banks, which had both
extended overdraft facilities of Pounds 4.5m. Other creditors included the
Inland Revenue, which was owed Pounds 1.5m.
The rest was made up of smaller creditors, including some 50 individuals. A
number of these later received compensation totalling Pounds 625,000 through
the Investors' Compensation Scheme. The largest individual investor was the
writer, Mr Frederick Forsyth, who lost some Pounds 900,000 through his
involvement in the company.
</TEXT>
