<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Second review of two counties is ordered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, yesterday ordered another review of
local government structure in Derbyshire and County Durham.
The move underlines the government's determination to do away with the
two-tier system of county and district councils used in rural England and
replace them with all-purpose 'unitary' authorities.
It also further undermines the position of the Local Government Commission,
chaired by Sir John Banham, charged with advising the government on the
review.
Sir John had recommended continuing the two-tier system in parts of both
counties, although he had suggested unitary status for Darlington, Derby,
and north-east Derbyshire.
His recommendations were made before Mr Gummer announced revised guidance
which made it clear that he expected unitary authorities to be the norm.
Uncertainty over local government in the two counties could now continue for
at least another year.
</TEXT>
