<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Prison officers can 'stop admittances'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prison officers have some legal powers which may have the effect of
disrupting admissions to prisons, an emergency conference of their union was
told yesterday.
Lawyers told delegates it was within officers' powers to refuse to allow new
inmates into overcrowded jails on the grounds that there was a risk of a
disturbance.
The High Court has ruled that the Prison Officers Association cannot call on
members to refuse admissions as part of their campaign against privatisation
of prisons. It ruled that prison officers had the legal status of
constables.
The POA executive yesterday argued that this legal status meant that
officers had a duty to prevent breaches of the peace. Mr John Bartell, the
POA chairman, said: 'Where officers believe there are likely to be
disturbances or disruption, they will be within their rights not to let new
inmates in. I have every reason to believe that will happen.'
The POA's tough response could signal a fresh period of prison service
unrest, first triggered by the High Court injunction which blocked the use
of locking out prisoners as a form of industrial action.
But the Home Office last night argued that the court ruling did not imply
any changes in the duties of prison officers, and it said officers had the
powers and privileges of a constable only when carrying out their duties as
laid down in prison rules. 'Preventing a breach of the peace is not
something that comes within their duties,' it said.
The Home Office insisted that it had no desire to take away prison officers'
employment protection rights when it sought the court injunction.
Mr Derek Lewis, director general of the Prison Service, said he hoped to
resume talks with the POA to place industrial relations on a 'proper
footing'.
He said the court ruling meant that a change in the law would probably be
needed for employment protection rights to be restored. Some trade unions
fear the government may try to legislate to prevent strikes in essential
services.
Mr Lewis said: 'We have made it crystal clear that we want the Prison
Officers Association and the Prison Governors Association and other unions
to continue to play an active part in the prison service.'
The status of the POA has also been called into question because most of its
members are classed as constables, and industrial relations law says a trade
dispute can only involve people classed as 'workers'. The Prison Governors'
Association is similarly affected.
The certification office of the Trade Union and Employers Associations is
reviewing the union's status. Mr Graham Osborne, assistant certification
officer, said: 'The judge has said they are not workers and if they are not
workers, they are not a trade union and if they are not a trade union they
cannot be on the list of trade unions.'
</TEXT>
