<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Unions sue over Tupe work rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Five unions yesterday issued writs against the government for failing
properly to implement the European Union's Acquired Rights Directive which
provides certain protections to employees in the event of a transfer of
ownership.
The government has recently rectified its implementation of the directive by
extending coverage to public-sector employees. But such employees who were
not covered between 1981 and 1993, and who suffered as a result, might be
able to claim damages after a ruling in the European Court of Justice.
The five unions - Unison, the public-service union; the TGWU and GMB general
unions; NUCPS, the civil service union; and the Northern Ireland Public
Service Alliance - have issued writs on behalf of 128 affected individuals.
The unions say that tens of thousands of people may have claims but that a
'negotiated settlement' is still on the table. The writs have been issued
now because any claims had to be registered within three months of the Trade
Union Reform and Employment Rights Act 1993 coming into operation. That act
corrected the omission of 'non-commercial' ventures from the Transfer of
Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations (Tupe), which
implemented the Acquired Rights Directive into British law.
</TEXT>
