<HEADLINE>
FT  30 NOV 93 / Labour urges Clarke to provide investment boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday urged Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to abandon the
imposition of value added tax on domestic fuel and to deliver a substantial
increase in investment in his first Budget today.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, told a meeting of backbench Labour
MPs that the Budget should maintain public services, introduce an emergency
job-creation programme and rebuild Britain's social and economic fabric.
Mr Brown also released a pamphlet, published by the Tribune group, setting
out details of his claim that tax revenues could be increased by Pounds 10bn
by closing tax loopholes.
The pamphlet argues for abolition of the Business Expansion Scheme, reform
of corporation tax, withdrawal of government plans to abolish stamp duty on
share transactions and a windfall tax on the profits of privatised
utilities.
In his speech Mr Brown said tax loopholes allowed many millionaires to pay
little or no tax, while many companies avoided their full share of taxation
by using offshore tax havens.
Mr Brown said that typical families already faced tax increases of Pounds
8.50 a week as a result of the last Budget. The imposition of VAT on
domestic fuel would further weaken those least able to cope.
Mr Brown said that tax reform would generate substantial funds to finance
both the abolition of VAT on domestic fuel and a 'business plan for Britain'
which would help create jobs and increase investment.
