<TEXT>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jim Bolger replaced Finance Minister Ruth
Richardson yesterday in a cabinet shake-up that could signal an end to
radical economic reforms, AP reports from Wellington.
This follows an election setback for Mr Bolger's National party, which saw
its parliamentary majority slashed from 34 seats to a single seat. Mr Bolger
blamed the rebuff on uncompromising free-market policies, the dismantling of
a highly regulated labour market, and cuts to New Zealand's generous welfare
system.
Ms Richardson, regarded as an architect of those policies, was replaced by
Mr Bill Birch, a former labor minister. She refused another cabinet job.
