<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Markets Report: Pound falls on profit taking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surprise news last Tuesday that base rates in the UK were finally coming
down after 10 months had the surprising effect of boosting sterling writes
Peter John.
The pound rose sharply against the D-Mark as investors who had already
hedged their positions against lower rates responded positively to the
possible boost to growth rather than the direct impact of lower interest
rates on the currency. However, by Friday, the gains were looking overdone
and the pound finally succumbed to profit-taking to close at DM2.5325.
The dollar continued to move in a tight range against the D - Mark of
between DM1.68 and DM1.72 but dealers said it was persistently showing
'upside pressure'. Much depends on key non-farm payroll data for November
due on Friday. The jobs figures are considered to be the most important
pointer to US economic trends and economists are looking for a rise over the
month of up to 200,000 jobs. A higher figure could see the US currency
heading for DM1.74.
</TEXT>
