<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1993 (31): VAT officers
go electronic / Customs and Excise application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Portable computers have replaced report forms in the briefcases of VAT
control officers visiting VAT-registered businesses and traders, writes John
Kavanagh.
The VATPACE system, developed by HM Customs and Excise and running on
Toshiba computers, helps officers check VAT returns and payments by
providing programs to handle tasks such as cash reconciliation and margin
calculations.
The officers write up their reports of their visits using an electronic
form, displayed on the computer screen. The Fillaform system is based on the
Formware software product from UK company European Printing Systems.
Formware can include facilities for validating information as it is keyed
in, for example to check numeric calculations. VAT officers use this
facility to check the likely validity of VAT registration numbers.
Formware prints the completed forms on plain paper, printing graphical items
such as a logo, boxes and ruled columns at the same time as the textual and
numeric information.
Before HM Customs and Excise introduced VATPACE and Fillaform, the visit
report forms were supplied on pre-printed stationery and were filled in by
hand.
The form includes details of all aspects of the visit, from the people
interviewed and the items checked to any over or under declarations and
action that was taken - 'managers can now read the completed forms more
easily,' says the VATPACE deputy project manager, Mr Phil Townsend.
'In addition, if a manager asks for extra information the form can easily be
amended. By the same token it is easy to change the form design through the
system.'
Other benefits arise from the fact that the system uses plain paper.
'Pre-printed stationery is expensive and takes storage space,' Mr Townsend
says. 'When the form design changes, the old stationery is wasted. We can
now use plain photocopier paper, which is much cheaper. And we only print
the forms we need, and when they are complete.'
The project team looked at using a standard word processing package before
settling on Formware.
'We needed a package with a powerful macro programming language which would
enable us to put in a front-end to the word processor to prompt the users
through the system,' Mr Townsend says. 'We decided the Fillaform idea was
easier and it's certainly worked out no more expensive.'
HM Customs and Excise has 1,500 VATPACE computers and its bulk purchasing
means it pays around Pounds 90 per computer to use Fillaform.
Contact: European Printing Systems, part of European Business Group, is on
(0329) 221121
</TEXT>
