<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1993 (30): Turnover
doubled / An address look-up system based on postcodes has helped holiday
company English Country Cottages to cut the time of telephone calls for
bookings by a third and improved accuracy and information
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
English Country Cottages sells self-catering holidays in 4,000 properties,
let on behalf of the owners, mainly in the UK but also now in Europe and New
England in the US.
Its annual Pounds 500,000 UK advertising budget produces 150,000 responses;
mailshots to 250,000 people bring in 75,000 enquiries; and 170,000 brochures
are sent to past customers. The company has 100 full-time and part-time
staff working from converted farm buildings in Fakenham, Norfolk, writes
John Kavanagh.
The company has doubled in turnover to Pounds 30m in the last five years and
puts much of its success down to its computer systems, running on ICL DRS
6000 equipment under the Unix operating system.
The booking system includes the Quickaddress package from UK firm QAS
Systems. This product is built around the Post Office's file of 1.7m
postcodes and 24.5m associated addresses.
The package produces complete addresses from a name and postcode or from
other partial and misspelt information. It can be used to clean up databases
and eliminate duplicates and to sort mailshots to give the best savings
through the Post Office's Mailsort discounts. Customised information
relating for example to sales territories or local authority wards can also
be held.
QAS Systems says the package cuts the number of keystrokes to enter an
address by up to 80 per cent if the postcode is known.
Many of these claims are confirmed by Mr Brian Soper, information technology
manager at English Country Cottages.
'A typical customer booking-call that used to take three minutes now only
takes two, and it now also includes all the confirmations we can provide,'
Mr Soper says.
Callers can now ask for properties in specific areas or near certain towns.
English Country Cottages sends property postcodes to QAS, which provides a
file linking postcodes to the holiday company's map references. Broad areas
can be entered and the system provides lists of properties in that area. The
address of the chosen property is transferred to the booking screen.
'Before we had this system we couldn't do such tightly-focused searches,'
Brian Soper says. 'Very few of our properties are in towns, so it was no use
searching by town name. Normally it meant searching by county, a much larger
area.'
Customers' own addresses are now generated automatically and accurately from
minimal information from the caller.
Operators can take credit or debit card payments and the booking system
checks the cards and authorises payments through on-line links to the
appropriate financial services organisations.
Telephone bookings are normally confirmed by the customer with a booking
form. Brian Soper says that because the use of Quickaddress guarantees the
address held by the system is accurate, it is no longer necessary to check
the address and postcode on the form.
'We are looking at eliminating booking forms and we couldn't do this without
knowing the address was accurate,' he says. 'We have very tight quality
assurance here.'
English Country Cottages paid Pounds 7,000 for Quickaddress. Prices range
from Pounds 875 for the first year and Pounds 250 for subsequent years for a
personal computer version to Pounds 35,000 and Pounds 9,000 for a system
running on a mainframe with more than 150 users. Maintenance ranges from
Pounds 275 to Pounds 12,000, including quarterly updates of the postcode
address file.
QAS Systems has 500 UK customers and is the biggest third-party outlet for
the postcode address file.
QAS was formed in 1990, and expects its turnover to grow 70 per cent in
1993-94 to Pounds 1.5m and net profit to grow from Pounds 10,000 to Pounds
200,000.
Contact: 081-675 6690.
Other companies in this market include GB Mailing Systems on (0829) 270714,
Capscan on 071-267 7055 and The Computing Group on (0293) 561666.
</TEXT>
