<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1993 (27):
Standardisation, a two-edged sword - Consultant's critique / Polygram and
DHL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In a stable operating environment, standardisation offers benefits via
economies of scale and reduced re-training. This is balanced by loss of
flexibility.
Standards can be applied to inputs, processes or outputs. For word
processing, input standards would cover such things as the layout of
documents, house styles and so on. Process standards would cover the
software package used and output standards would apply to the file formats
used.
POLYGRAM has chosen to standardise processes and outputs by insisting on the
use of Wordperfect only. Mr John Higgins, the group's director of
information technology, claims that this gives massive savings. It could
equally be argued that companies buying in the quantities claimed by
Polygram can also obtain considerable discounts, providing similar scope for
savings.
A commitment to a single vendor has advantages but also carries risks. Once
a supplier knows that a customer is locked in by an agreement, the balance
of power shifts subtly. Many large companies deliberately avoid such
agreements in order to keep vendors on their toes.
In a changing software market, a commitment to a sole supplier can prevent a
company from taking advantage of new software trends. Wordperfect was slow
in coming outwith a Windows version of its software. Indeed, Microsoft was
able to tempt away Wordperfect users by offering a migration path on to its
Word for Windows package.
Mr Higgins clearly believes in keeping tight control, though obviously this
does impose extra costs of monitoring and verification. Staff entering
Polygram who are already very familiar with a different package will need to
be re-trained.
DHL has a more flexible approach and does not appear to standardise as much.
They admit that they lose some formatting when transferring documents via
the Uniplex system.
If the object is to increase connectivity, it is usually better to
standardise on outputs - such as a standard file format, rather than the
processes. Both companies could simply insist on a common file format (say,
the Wordperfect format) which all packages must support to be approved. Most
of the leading word processors can read each other's formats. It would be
sensible to select one that all the software can use and then insist that
everyone generates that format.
Given that the aim is to produce readable documents, it might even be better
to move the focus on to presentation. I have seen far too many documents
that are poorly laid out or which contain spelling errors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Polygram International.
    DHL International UK.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
