<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1993 (12): Finding out
where Welsh water flows - Utility application / For Dwr Cymru, Welsh Water,
the geographical information system is at the centre of its efforts to
document its assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Underground pipes and overground cables pose some of the thorniest problems
when taking stock of assets. Dwr Cymru, Welsh Water, is the water and
sewerage authority for Wales, and like many utilities, is taking a long-term
view of its assets and investments, writes Claire Gooding.
Welsh Water's Integrated Business Information System (Ibis) is part of its
Pounds 1.9bn investment programme, a set of integrated applications which
will provide a complete record of every aspect of Welsh Water's operations.
'The first thing was, that as a company, we needed a good asset base,'
explains Peter Lindsay, network asset manager. 'We had a multitude of
systems holding data of various states of quality and completeness,
scattered over the 21,000 sq km in which we operate.
'We realised we needed manageable systems, and, by the regulations which
brought about privatisation in 1989, we are required to keep accurate
records of underground assets.'
Consultants Coopers and Lybrand assisted in the search for a geographical
product, which started in 1989. It included test runs and bench marks of
products from SIA, IBM, and Intergraph. But it was Intergraph that impressed
Welsh Water most when it came to meeting the long-term objectives, and its
'co-operative attitude' secured a contract worth about Pounds 3.5m on
software, hardware and services. The negotiations for new water contracts
were the driver for early completion.
'We accelerated the seven-year programme to a two-year programme to be able
to capitalise on the benefits of sound, reliable data on our underground
assets,' says Mr Lindsay.
The Assets Information System built using the Intergraph system went live in
April. The largest of the 24 IBIS modules, it is a database which contains
all the maps and precise graphic, locational and descriptive details of all
under and above-ground assets. It is integrated with the business reporting
systems such as customer accounts, leakage reports and electricity usage.
'The next step is to get operational benefits, support services, efficient
record keeping, and to be able to access all data on surveys. On-line
real-time information could be valuable for such things as tracing burst
water mains,' says Lindsay.
He is now looking at expanding the use of the system into other departments,
such as estates, legal, and planning. The aim is to populate the database
with OPCS census data, and with geographical information for a 'land
terrier' (asset register) and estates system, showing boundaries such as
ancient monuments - 'there is company-wide enthusiasm, and groups of users
steering its development,' he says.
</TEXT>
