<HEADLINE>
FT  29 NOV 93 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1993 (6): Insight on
sites - User view / Property portfolio management / Large retail chains need
efficient property management. In the UK, Boots Properties uses a GIS to
analyse its portfolio. The business is already benefiting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the UK retail property market, Boots Properties' retail portfolio is one
of the largest, including high street and out-of-town sites, writes Claire
Gooding. Boots believes that a key source of competitive advantage is the
strong emphasis it places on research to inform its business decisions.
'We recognise that the retail property market is inefficient,' says Mike
Dutton, business development and research manager. 'This presents a clear
opportunity for well-informed investors to enhance the performance of their
portfolio.'
Site location analysis involves many different variables and indicators.
Boots Properties needed a product that would work at postcode sector level,
with a wide range of census data. Most important was the ability to forecast
the performance of specific local property markets and properties in the
portfolio.
The chosen solution, CACI's InSite system, was PC-based, user friendly, and
provided detailed population forecasts. Boots Properties deliberately bought
a group licence to encourage widespread use of the system by other
businesses such as Boots The Chemists, Halfords, and Childrens World, for
their own market research and estates management.
Using OPCS census data, other bought-in consumer analyses, together with
in-house proprietary sales data, the GIS team looks at such factors as the
balance of supply and demand in the local retail property market, whether
the market is over-pricing or under-pricing a certain town, and determining
the prospects for rental growth.
The analysis is carried further using the SPSS analytical software,
integrating data about supply and demand from a wide range of databases and
different computers. Dutton is convinced that the GIS, in use since
September 1992, has already benefited the business. 'We're concerned to
maintain and enhance the asset value, and this system gives us the ability
to do that more effectively,' he says.
Better-informed decisions will result from the GIS, he concludes, and it
should be much easier to exploit market inefficiencies, especially with the
benefit of up-up-to-date census data.
</TEXT>
